London Henry Colliur
Sr. my last to you was on the 26: pass. sence rec. yd of 21 ditto as to the concences
of T.SS. I doubt vere much that, you will finde nothing butt words, for the oldman
iusted of paying the charges, sayes to m. Herreynce that you shall finde itt wih
the capitall, which I supose will be never, butt what soever Iwte, desire you
not to mention, mee butt as if all you had from herreynce yd self & tell
boath you uy hert opp & bigheley freely, that the old man refused to pay the
charges in alaring mannes, so that herreynce he told mee plainly that m.
hart op never thought to pay charges nor capital for which should be sorry
Icould wish he were in a good condition, for heis aman that ever y onee here
laves, and his soim is vere well estemeed, will doubtless be advanced
as for trade itt is not onely with you, butt more dead with us here to
which the late french invasion & spoyl hath al most gen the last
blew, whach o doubt not butt you will understand fromall hav, inclosed
one from John button who makes aworld full of complaints atells
mee that were fromrly ke sold att . mislaes faire day for 6 a ƒ 700:-
in goods he sold now for £6: flemish, so that I doubt you will have
some thing to of itt whilst he refuse the to accept yd bill till he
hath yd answer here unto, whoever yd sonmes shall finde due
complayneede hale don somck aspossibly croulld to discharge ydbill
17 without redrawins, butt that of 30 ditto & can notaroid
though much agaiest mij honnour, so have past mj bills of paule
cloots for the ratw of aquespoyon, onue for satie I say £60s
of y. curitt 2 uso to the of pauls cloots for the valew of Garques tsandes
the other of this day for £60:- to the order of m. Arthur Aimeslay
att 2 uso boath att 35:4 which please to qive due honnour place
to yd acctt. nowas for acctt. I am in so good a forwardness that
& supose few dayes in canuarynext will bring them all for I have
in
time enough dagly to be about them & Immust ballance itt curitt
according to our custume, so have now solons patience you desine to
draw more mony, you know what I wrott before & in case times go
on with us, as he ther to they have don then & feare there will be no
trade attall, soam resoluld to desest much mor in allmanner
of drawing, trully you lived here & saee things as they goyon
would finde reason to beame yd freind that should be sp argent as yoo
are & that is all I have to say whils remaine
t London Arthur Aneslay
S. in answer to yd of 25: past. returne you thanckes for yd readiness in
providing the 2 bales to putt off the rest off aur goods here for my
half patt in their cost have given you creditt. & shall exspect the pattarnes accordingly
to yd promise yd bill shall finde due complayance & be past to bookas you
order ony acctt. you have here in closed £bo mare att 2 uso
on mr. Herpij Collier for which please to procure the needfull & passt
yd acctt. att 35:4: our ordinary time for acctts is ult. xb., so god, willing
you may depend up onitt, to have yd att large, for bram in a good for wardnitt

& so remaine

Antw: 10 xb 1681
Sr. I have before mee yd of 14: past when by am glad to understand that you had receave
the laces & sireen. as for laces now they are so cheap, that never the like hath
been, so that I shall complent yd order much to content & assort the maccording
to the last orders I have out of England of 25: past. which & do not doubt butt will
prove well & wee send not muchopen lace, or holes, which wee eall without gotund
butt some, of antwrp laces of which you had non, so shall endeavour al
much as possible to incorridge you of which I do not in the least doubt, because
wee can have now what we will of sorts & really cleap so you may dependupon
my care to comply with yd diretious I have wate for ostend Rotterdam toknow
what conveniendey there is for schipping for Diblin to dispatch the goods the
stoneft & shall alcording to yd orders valew mij self on mr. George Cole & so with

Sr. my last to you was on the 24: pas to which please to be heferred sence is John
simons wall arrived, butt the goods are yett att Bruges intrim inclosed is my bill
for £60: on mr. Edmund varneratt 2 uso for which please to procure the needfull
& pass to my acctt. I hope the time shall not in commode you if itt doth
please rather to draw omnee Icould wish to have some Jauroias, & reds as
last desired of which please to take noticie when areasonable pennuwoith
presents whilst I could be gladd I could do you some service with my tykes &
I am some what confuse with yd kersies because I can not stersuade any of
my customers to buy fheim therefore mee thinckes that if they were sent in holantor
returned to you, you should make much more then I shall be able todo:
the y pay no charges out wadl

Sr. sence mj last to you on the 3 curitt wee have been much allannes by a french
London Comune Warner
nicassion between gant & bruges up on apretended acctt. of represailles, so that the
passage from hence to newnort was not secure & therefore dewed send non
of the packetts butt this day wee understand that they are retired & all
passages secured of our pedile, so shall now proceed p. next to send the rest of
yd goods as also what you have in ordered by yd of 21. nast viz 2 p. of crawatt
from 10 to 15 guld with dubles supes 3p. for coawats plaine ground which you
say must be ss of 5 p 10f 9 t & one a 15 a 16. which i supose you meand
shillings flemish, because before you wrott of guld. such sort wee have they
beeng for the vere common sort of peorle not altoghether to broad as
others, you shall have all withing 2 post colserve that dayly you finde
more reason to complains, which you should not do in case you wasised
to yd ex. peoples honneurs for though goods be never so chear they will
alwayes abate more & more & will persuade & tell you thousand floriss, &
nay lie from one month to another send goods to 4 a 5 severall freind
in london & ded for a long while & have of late clarge commissions from
them as also out of grlante, I am confident they understand the
trade, for 2 of them are setved yett of another besidas mee & in case they
loeindimy doyng, if not better, att least nott al others Iam confident
they would not continew, butt now please to bb serve is the worst time
of the yeare & towards spring you will finde itt much better whilst pro
intrim you may make what advantage of itt you can, andif sobe you
finde any peeces & which would not sell to yd content, & proffitt, returne them
though & didnor do send, butt what others do also demanded, except itt be the head
flowers in the antwarp laces, which somes times they will, & some times not so
well, whoever they can be returned for by no meanes may you haven any
thoughts to onderalewe what I send & to prevent yd further complaints do nick
out for you out of all parcells, what penny worths there are which I shall
mack with a private ssigne, or in the invoyce please to advise me il you
sinde no fautt by the pressing or making up of the packetts, that there
bj the laces, should sauffer & make the tread the courser here before scould
butt in one packett ƒ750:- & never were they almost as bigg as now one
of ƒ550: a ƒ 600:- so that laces are dogh cheap & people can hardely hul by
them that makes y. I shall make up one packett in the manner as fthomas
stanep is iused to do, to see if his way will please you bester butt pray heer that
to yds self I have this day sent my bill tou huy knightley for £60
